1

00:00:08,240  -->  00:00:09,060
Hello, everyone!

2

00:00:09,060  -->  00:00:11,320
It’s me, Alex.

3

00:00:11,320  -->  00:00:14,860
Today’s lesson will be about a little bit of grammar.

4

00:00:14,860  -->  00:00:17,230
However, it isn’t
particularly difficult.

5

00:00:17,230  -->  00:00:22,140
We’ll tackle the aspect of negation.
This refers to expressing

6

00:00:22,140  -->  00:00:24,100
how something is not.

7

00:00:24,100  -->  00:00:25,960
We’ve already come across this aspect,

8

00:00:25,960  -->  00:00:30,699
especially during dictation.
Today I will show you

9

00:00:30,700  -->  00:00:38,380
the most important rules about negation
in the German language.

10

00:00:38,380  -->  00:00:43,800
There are two possibilities. You can either
use “any/no”

11

00:00:43,800  -->  00:00:45,720
or “not”.

12

00:00:45,720  -->  00:00:49,300
I will show you how to use them correctly in a sentence.

13

00:00:49,300  -->  00:00:53,340
“Not” is used more often than “any/no”.

14

00:00:53,340  -->  00:00:57,560
We can use “not” for: negation of verbs,

15

00:00:57,560  -->  00:01:01,320
of some nouns, of
proper names,

16

00:01:01,320  -->  00:01:08,520
of adjectives, of pronouns, of adverbs,
when indicating the place,

17

00:01:08,520  -->  00:01:15,080
the time and the manner,
the way in which

18

00:01:15,080  -->  00:01:16,860
something is being done.

19

00:01:16,860  -->  00:01:21,620
“Any/no” is only used for nouns

20

00:01:21,630  -->  00:01:26,090
without an article. When the noun has
no article,

21

00:01:26,090  -->  00:01:35,120
then we use “any/no” and “any/no”
substitutes an indefinite article.

22

00:01:35,120  -->  00:01:41,080
I’ll explain to you what this means
in a few minutes.

23

00:01:41,080  -->  00:01:45,580
Verbs. How to form the negation using
“not”.

24

00:01:45,580  -->  00:01:54,460
When there’s no auxiliary verb -
relevant for us is the present tense -

25

00:01:54,460  -->  00:01:57,100
we use “not” for verbs.

26

00:01:57,100  -->  00:02:01,140
If there’s no auxiliary verb, “not” is placed at the end of a sentence,

27

00:02:01,140  -->  00:02:05,020
If there is an auxiliary verb, “not” is placed before the main verb.

28

00:02:05,020  -->  00:02:08,220
The tenses with auxiliary verbs aren’t that important at the moment.

29

00:02:08,220  -->  00:02:10,640
Only as an example.

30

00:02:10,640  -->  00:02:15,420
The present tense doesn’t require an auxiliary verb:

31

00:02:15,420  -->  00:02:20,480
She does not eat. “Not” is placed at the end of the sentence.

32

00:02:20,480  -->  00:02:24,800
Or: The child has not eaten.

33

00:02:24,800  -->  00:02:28,880
“Not” is placed before the main verb, which is placed at the end
of the sentence.

34

00:02:28,880  -->  00:02:35,300
This tense is called “present perfect” in German
and is one of the three past tenses.

35

00:02:35,300  -->  00:02:40,380
You needn’t know this yet.
However, it would be nice to know

36

00:02:40,380  -->  00:02:45,480
why this young woman isn’t eating.

37

00:02:47,960  -->  00:02:49,020
Proper names.

38

00:02:49,020  -->  00:02:56,900
For proper names we use the negation with “not”:
This is not Markus. This is Peter.

39

00:02:57,560  -->  00:03:02,880
That person, that is not Markus.
It is Peter.

40

00:03:02,880  -->  00:03:08,620
Nouns with a definite article or before possessive pronouns.

41

00:03:08,620  -->  00:03:12,380
Possessive pronouns are not that important at the moment,

42

00:03:12,380  -->  00:03:15,180
but nouns with a definite article are.

43

00:03:15,180  -->  00:03:20,280
For example: The pupils have not written their homework,

44

00:03:20,280  -->  00:03:25,400
but have played football.
It’s all about this article, here.

45

00:03:25,400  -->  00:03:30,100
If it were not there, we would need
to use “any/not”.

46

00:03:30,100  -->  00:03:37,180
However: The pupils have not written their
homework, but have played football.

47

00:03:37,180  -->  00:03:41,360
And let’s be honest. When we were
their age, we also

48

00:03:41,360  -->  00:03:48,160
would have rather played football,
than write our homework.

49

00:03:52,560  -->  00:04:01,920
We also use “not” for adjectives:
This is not good! Or: This is not bad!

50

00:04:01,920  -->  00:04:08,160
This is not good. Here, thumbs down.

51

00:04:08,160  -->  00:04:14,560
For pronouns we also use the negation with “not”:

52

00:04:14,560  -->  00:04:23,620
He has not spoken with us, but with them.

53

00:04:23,620  -->  00:04:27,100
Here, “not” refers to
“us”.

54

00:04:27,100  -->  00:04:31,120
Not with us. “Not” is placed before the pronoun.

55

00:04:31,120  -->  00:04:37,500
And here: She is not fond of you, but of someone else.

56

00:04:37,500  -->  00:04:43,960
She is not fond of you, but of someone else.

57

00:04:43,960  -->  00:04:46,700
“Not” stands before the pronoun

58

00:04:46,700  -->  00:04:51,660
and that is how to use the negation for pronouns.

59

00:04:53,520  -->  00:04:58,220
For adverbs we also use the negation with “not”:

60

00:04:58,220  -->  00:05:01,040
He does not write his homework willingly.

61

00:05:01,040  -->  00:05:07,180
Here, a frustrated little boy. He does not write his homework willingly.

62

00:05:07,180  -->  00:05:10,940
“Willingly” is an adverb.

63

00:05:10,940  -->  00:05:18,720
Adverbs are always connected to
verbs. This is why they are called “ad-verbs”.

64

00:05:18,720  -->  00:05:23,480
And “not” is used to negate these adverbs.

65

00:05:23,480  -->  00:05:26,460
This means that he writes his homework,

66

00:05:26,460  -->  00:05:31,700
but not willingly. This is why
“not” refers to the adverb

67

00:05:31,700  -->  00:05:33,520
and not to the verb,

68

00:05:33,520  -->  00:05:37,860
because he does write his homework, but not willingly.

69

00:05:37,860  -->  00:05:42,940
I can relate to this little boy
very much.

70

00:05:46,240  -->  00:05:54,220
Adverbs of place, time and manner
are also negated using “not”:

71

00:05:55,100  -->  00:06:01,840
I am not from Frankfurt.

72

00:06:01,840  -->  00:06:10,920
I won’t come to you at 12 o’clock tomorrow.

73

00:06:10,920  -->  00:06:19,380
And here: He does not eat with a knife and a fork.

74

00:06:19,380  -->  00:06:21,880
Well, with what then?

75

00:06:25,120  -->  00:06:31,780
Very important! “Not” is almost always
placed in front of the negated object.

76

00:06:31,780  -->  00:06:38,420
Before pronouns, adverbs of place, adverbs of time,
adverbs in general, adjectives, proper names.

77

00:06:38,420  -->  00:06:43,120
“Not” is always placed in front of the negated
object.

78

00:06:43,120  -->  00:06:46,980
The only exception: the verb.

79

00:06:46,980  -->  00:06:50,120
It can happen that “not” does not

80

00:06:50,120  -->  00:06:52,900
stand before a verb, but at the end of a sentence,

81

00:06:52,900  -->  00:06:56,880
as we have seen
in our first example.

82

00:06:56,880  -->  00:06:59,720
She does not eat.

83

00:07:03,260  -->  00:07:05,020
Let’s move on to “any/no”.

84

00:07:05,020  -->  00:07:11,940
The second possibility in order to form a negation in German.

85

00:07:11,940  -->  00:07:14,440
Nouns without an article.

86

00:07:14,440  -->  00:07:20,000
Nouns without an article are negated using “any/no”
and not using “not”.

87

00:07:20,000  -->  00:07:30,659
I eat spaghetti. I don’t eat any spaghetti.
I don’t eat any spaghetti.

88

00:07:30,660  -->  00:07:36,980
If “spaghetti” had a definite article -
“I eat the spaghetti.” -

89

00:07:36,980  -->  00:07:41,560
then it should be: “I do not eat the spaghetti.”

90

00:07:41,560  -->  00:07:43,940
“Not” at the end of the sentence.

91

00:07:43,940  -->  00:07:50,200
But because there is no article
here, no definite article:

92

00:07:50,200  -->  00:07:54,080
“I don’t eat any spaghetti.”

93

00:07:56,660  -->  00:08:02,680
This is how “any” substitutes an indefinite article,

94

00:08:02,680  -->  00:08:06,680
so “a” and “an”.

95

00:08:06,680  -->  00:08:16,240
There is a fish. There is a fish. And:
There is no fish. There is no fish.

96

00:08:16,240  -->  00:08:22,990
“No” is substituting “a”
and “a” is an indefinite article.

97

00:08:25,800  -->  00:08:33,020
And the rule: “Any” or “no” stand before the
negated thing. It’s relatively easy.

98

00:08:37,100  -->  00:08:44,240
Now it’s time for a short test.
Please read these questions or

99

00:08:44,240  -->  00:08:48,720
these sentences,
then stop the video,

100

00:08:48,720  -->  00:08:52,180
try to form a negation,

101

00:08:52,180  -->  00:08:56,160
and then I will show you the solution.

102

00:08:56,160  -->  00:09:03,780
The child is playing. I have slept.
I have bought the clothes.

103

00:09:03,780  -->  00:09:14,280
This is Peter’s bicycle. This is nice.
I like going to the restaurant.

104

00:09:14,280  -->  00:09:16,920
I live in Tokyo.

105

00:09:16,920  -->  00:09:23,700
He arrives at 9 p.m. I am thirsty.

106

00:09:23,700  -->  00:09:26,280
This is a fish.

107

00:09:26,280  -->  00:09:31,640
Now you can stop the video, you can try to find out

108

00:09:31,640  -->  00:09:39,720
where to use “not” or “any/no” and
I will show you the solution shortly after.

109

00:09:39,720  -->  00:09:44,580
And now I’m going to show you how
to use the negation,

110

00:09:44,580  -->  00:09:48,880
where to insert the word “not”.

111

00:09:48,880  -->  00:09:50,920
The child is not playing.

112

00:09:50,920  -->  00:09:56,440
The rule: If there’s no auxiliary verb, “not” stands at the end of the sentence.

113

00:09:56,440  -->  00:09:59,400
I have not slept.

114

00:09:59,400  -->  00:10:03,460
If there is an auxiliary verb, this is
the auxiliary verb,

115

00:10:03,460  -->  00:10:08,880
“not” stands before the main verb at the end of the sentence.

116

00:10:08,880  -->  00:10:14,600
I have not slept.
I have not bought the clothes.

117

00:10:14,600  -->  00:10:20,220
I have not bought the clothes.
The same rule applies.

118

00:10:20,220  -->  00:10:28,860
This is not Peter’s bicycle. This is not
Peter’s bicycle. “Peter’s bicycle” is negated,

119

00:10:28,860  -->  00:10:34,540
which is why “not” stands right in front of it.
This is not nice. “Nice” is an adjective,

120

00:10:34,540  -->  00:10:40,000
“not” stands before it: This is not nice.

121

00:10:40,000  -->  00:10:44,380
I do not like going to the restaurant.

122

00:10:44,380  -->  00:10:51,080
I do not like going to the restaurant. Again,
the negation using “not”.

123

00:10:51,080  -->  00:10:57,279
I do not live in Tokyo. I do not live
in Tokyo.

124

00:10:57,280  -->  00:11:03,700
He does not arrive at 9 p.m. He does not arrive
at 9 p.m.

125

00:11:03,700  -->  00:11:15,920
I am not thirsty. I am not thirsty.
And: This is no fish. This is no fish.

126

00:11:15,920  -->  00:11:22,160
As you can see, excepting the present tense,
if there’s no auxiliary verb,

127

00:11:22,160  -->  00:11:25,660
“not” always stands in front of the negated thing.

128

00:11:25,660  -->  00:11:28,560
It isn’t that difficult.

129

00:11:30,280  -->  00:11:33,240
For the last part of the lesson I’ve
prepared,

130

00:11:33,240  -->  00:11:38,060
as I often do, a short dictation.

131

00:11:38,060  -->  00:11:41,760
I’ll start with the first sentence.

132

00:14:29,100  -->  00:14:34,760
Super! This is it for today. I’m going to quickly
show you the solution

133

00:14:34,760  -->  00:14:40,500
and then we can also not go to bed
at 10 p.m.

134

00:14:40,500  -->  00:14:48,800
I do not wake up in the morning. I do not wake up
in the morning.

135

00:14:48,800  -->  00:14:53,980
As you can see, “not” doesn’t really
stand at the end of the sentence.

136

00:14:53,980  -->  00:15:00,760
This is because of this particle. In German
there is a peculiarity

137

00:15:00,760  -->  00:15:03,840
called “separable verbs”.

138

00:15:03,840  -->  00:15:06,340
I won’t go into detail about it today.

139

00:15:06,340  -->  00:15:11,060
We will discuss it in a couple of lessons.

140

00:15:11,060  -->  00:15:14,340
This particle would

141

00:15:14,340  -->  00:15:16,000
basically stand here.

142

00:15:16,000  -->  00:15:19,140
“To wake up” is the infinitive, which is why

143

00:15:19,140  -->  00:15:22,380
“not” is viewed as standing at the end of the sentence.

144

00:15:22,380  -->  00:15:25,820
But you don’t need to know this for the time being.

145

00:15:25,820  -->  00:15:34,100
I do not go to work by car. I do not
go to work by car.

146

00:15:34,100  -->  00:15:41,240
I do not work in Berlin. I do not work
in Berlin.

147

00:15:41,240  -->  00:15:48,340
I do not like working. I do not like
working.

148

00:15:48,350  -->  00:15:57,520
We have no television at home.
Please remember:

149

00:15:57,520  -->  00:16:00,100
“Television” has no article,

150

00:16:00,100  -->  00:16:03,740
which is why we need “no”.

151

00:16:03,740  -->  00:16:13,820
We do not go to bed at 10 p.m.

152

00:16:15,900  -->  00:16:17,460
That was it for today.

153

00:16:17,460  -->  00:16:19,680
I’ll bid goodbye for today.

154

00:16:19,680  -->  00:16:23,660
It has been fun to be here with you again.

155

00:16:23,660  -->  00:16:26,860
I wish you all the best, a nice evening

156

00:16:26,860  -->  00:16:28,500
and I hope to see you next time.

157

